  "prompt": "Why did China again object to India's bid at UN to ban JeM chief Masood Azhar?",
  "response": "China has once again objected to India's bid at the United Nations to ban Jaish-e-Mohammed (JeM) chief Masood Azhar, putting a technical hold on the proposal. This move by China, a veto-wielding permanent member of the UN Security Council, effectively blocks the ban for the fourth time since 2009.\n\nThere are several reasons why China may have objected to the ban:\n\n1. **Strategic Interests**: China and Pakistan have close strategic, military, and economic ties. China may be protecting its ally Pakistan by blocking the ban on Azhar, who is a Pakistani national.\n\n2. **CPEC**: The China-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC), a flagship project of China's Belt and Road Initiative, runs through Pakistan. China may want to maintain good relations with Pakistan to ensure the smooth implementation of this project.\n\n3. **India-China Relations**: China and India have had a tense relationship in recent years, with border disputes and competition for regional influence. China's objection to the ban could be seen as a way to counter India's growing influence on the global stage.\n\n4. **UN Sanctions**: China has argued that the issue of banning Azhar should be dealt with through the UN's 1267 Committee, which focuses on sanctions related to terrorism. China believes that the ban should be considered in the context of the committee's work, rather than as a standalone proposal.\n\nIt is worth noting that China's objection to the ban has drawn criticism from other countries, including the United States, France, and the United Kingdom, who co-sponsored the proposal along with India.",
